        <!-- Part 1: Current Regulations -->
        <div class="mb-5">
          <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">Part 1: Current Regulations (Prior to April 2025)</h2>
          <p class="mb-4">The current framework is primarily governed by the <strong>Decreto 113/2015</strong>, which established the legal basis for holiday rentals in the Canary Islands.</p>
          
          <h3 class="h4 mb-3">Key Requirements for a VV License:</h3>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Legal Standing</h4>
            <p>The property must be classified as a <strong>Vivienda Vacacional</strong>, defined as a furnished property rented as a whole, for short-term stays.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Exclusions</h4>
            <div class="alert alert-warning" role="alert">
              <strong>Important:</strong> Rentals are strictly prohibited in tourist areas, tourist developments, and mixed residential-tourist developments, as defined by local zoning plans. This is a crucial and often overlooked restriction.
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Registration Process</h4>
            <p>To legally operate, you must submit a <strong>Declaración Responsable</strong> (a sworn declaration of compliance) to the relevant local authority. The property must then be registered in the <strong>Registro General Turístico</strong> of the Canary Islands.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Mandatory Documentation</h4>
            <p class="mb-3">The application requires a comprehensive set of documents, including:</p>
            <ul class="mb-3">
              <li>Title deeds (Escritura)</li>
              <li>Registration with the IGIC (Impuesto General Indirecto Canario) tax authority</li>
              <li>Energy Efficiency Certificate (Certificado de eficiencia energética)</li>
              <li>Floor plans of the property</li>
              <li>Valid public liability insurance (Seguro de responsabilidad civil)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Property Standards</h4>
            <p>The property must meet specific standards, including a minimum habitable surface area (often 25m² for studios), a visible identifier plaque (placa-distintivo), and an emergency information board in multiple languages.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Part 2: New Regulations -->
        <div class="mb-5">
          <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">Part 2: New Regulations for 2025 and Onward</h2>
          <p class="mb-4">A new law, effective from <strong>April 3, 2025</strong>, introduces significant changes aimed at regulating the market and addressing the housing crisis. These regulations mark a major shift from the previous framework.</p>
          
          <h3 class="h4 mb-3">Key Changes and New Compliance Obligations:</h3>
          
          <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
              <div class="card h-100 border-0 bg-light">
                <div class="card-body">
                  <h5 class="card-title">Community of Owners Approval</h5>
                  <ul class="mb-0">
                    <li>Under the new law, a vacation rental is no longer permitted by default</li>
                    <li>Properties within a Community of Owners must now obtain a <strong>three-fifths (60%) majority vote</strong> from the community</li>
                    <li>Communities can impose a <strong>surcharge of up to 20%</strong> on community fees for tourist rentals</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
              <div class="card h-100 border-0 bg-light">
                <div class="card-body">
                  <h5 class="card-title">Property Age Requirement</h5>
                  <p class="mb-0">Any new VV license application for properties must be for a building that is <strong>at least 10 years old</strong>.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">New Registration System</h4>
            <p>From <strong>July 2, 2025</strong>, a new national, unified registry system, the <strong>Ventanilla Única</strong>, will be implemented. This system is designed to create a single point of registration for all tourist accommodation in Spain.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">"Zonas Tensionadas" (Stressed Areas)</h4>
            <p class="mb-2">The new law introduces the concept of <strong>zonas tensionadas</strong>, where local municipalities can suspend the issuance of new licenses for up to five years to protect residential housing.</p>
            <div class="alert alert-info" role="alert">
              <strong>Implementation is underway:</strong> Municipalities like Las Palmas de Gran Canaria and Adeje have already begun the process of declaring themselves as stressed areas.
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">"Uso Turístico Consolidado" (Consolidated Tourist Use)</h4>
            <p>This new provision allows municipalities to recognize specific areas where tourist use is already well-established. This could potentially protect existing rentals in certain locations from the new restrictions.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Part 3: Ongoing Compliance -->
        <div class="mb-5">
          <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">Part 3: Ongoing Compliance & Tax Obligations</h2>
          <p class="mb-4">Beyond the initial license, owners must adhere to continuous compliance requirements.</p>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Guest Registration</h4>
            <p>All guests must be registered with the relevant authorities. The new national online platform for this is <strong>SES. HOSPEDAJES</strong>, which replaced older regional systems as of 2025. Property owners are required to submit the personal details of all guests to the authorities (National Police or Guardia Civil) within 24 hours of check-in.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Taxation</h4>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                <div class="card border-start border-4" style="border-color: #b39c84 !important;">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h5 class="card-title">IGIC</h5>
                    <p class="mb-0">Short-term rental income is subject to the Canary Islands' General Indirect Tax (IGIC) at a rate of <strong>7%</strong>.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                <div class="card border-start border-4" style="border-color: #b39c84 !important;">
                  <div class="card-body">
                    <h5 class="card-title">Income Tax</h5>
                    <p class="mb-0">Owners must pay income tax on their rental earnings. The rate is <strong>19% for EU residents</strong>, Norway, or Iceland, and <strong>24% for non-EU residents</strong>.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Part 4: Future Regulations -->
        <div class="mb-5">
          <h2 class="h3 mb-4" style="color: #b39c84;">Part 4: Potential Future Regulations & Political Context</h2>
          <p class="mb-4">The regulatory landscape is highly dynamic and subject to ongoing political debate.</p>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Proposed Amendments</h4>
            <p>The current law has been subject to legislative discussion, with proposals for further restrictions being considered. For example, some political parties have proposed limiting the number of VV licenses to a maximum of three per owner to curb speculation, although this has not been adopted as of now.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="h5 mb-3">Stakeholder Conflict</h4>
            <p>There is a clear divide between different interest groups. Rural tourism associations are advocating for stricter enforcement to protect their businesses, while a platform of small owners feels targeted by regulations that favor large tourist operators.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SEO Benefits -->
